1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,800
Now, once we have implemented a single block,

2

00:00:02,800  -->  00:00:07,260
let's take a look at how we can assemble everything into a single model.

3

00:00:07,260  -->  00:00:10,640
We'll first walk through all the components of the model,

4

00:00:10,640  -->  00:00:12,060
and in the next demo,

5

00:00:12,060  -->  00:00:14,640
we will write it using PyTorch.

6

00:00:14,640  -->  00:00:16,240
As we've discussed before,

7

00:00:16,240  -->  00:00:18,790
to pass an input to our model.

8

00:00:18,790  -->  00:00:21,180
We need to split it into tokens,

9

00:00:21,180  -->  00:00:25,400
such as words, sub words, or individual characters.

10

00:00:25,400  -->  00:00:29,160
Then we need to convert tokens into token IDs.

11

00:00:29,160  -->  00:00:33,860
We then convert the token IDs into embedding vectors.

12

00:00:33,860  -->  00:00:36,940
Then we add positional encoding values,

13

00:00:36,940  -->  00:00:42,140
and the result of this sum are the input vectors we are sending to our model.

14

00:00:42,140  -->  00:00:46,220
We then pass this input to the first layer of our network.

15

00:00:46,220  -->  00:00:51,465
We then pass the output of this layer to the next layer, and so on.

16

00:00:51,465  -->  00:00:55,550
The output from each layer has the same shape as the input,

17

00:00:55,550  -->  00:00:59,460
but the value of embedding vectors change from layer to layer.

18

00:00:59,460  -->  00:01:01,470
When we are training our model,

19

00:01:01,470  -->  00:01:03,970
we will not pass just a single input.

20

00:01:03,970  -->  00:01:09,110
We'll pass a batch of inputs together to use our resources more efficiently.

21

00:01:09,110  -->  00:01:12,050
Finally, after the final layer of our model,

22

00:01:12,050  -->  00:01:15,830
we need to convert the output into the next predicted token.

23

00:01:15,830  -->  00:01:20,370
The output from the last layer will have the same number of embedding vectors,

24

00:01:20,370  -->  00:01:23,150
and we need to convert it into tokens.

25

00:01:23,150  -->  00:01:25,190
We do it in two steps.

26

00:01:25,190  -->  00:01:31,000
First, we use a linear layer to convert each embedding vector into a new vector.

27

00:01:31,000  -->  00:01:35,630
That contains prediction scores for each of the tokens in our vocabulary.

28

00:01:35,630  -->  00:01:39,530
For example, 039, in this case is how confident

29

00:01:39,530  -->  00:01:43,990
are model that it should generate token with 80 in this position.

30

00:01:43,990  -->  00:01:45,730
The higher the prediction score,

31

00:01:45,730  -->  00:01:50,170
the higher the model is confidence that it should use this token ID.

32

00:01:50,170  -->  00:01:55,225
But we then want to convert these values into probability distributions.

33

00:01:55,225  -->  00:01:56,930
As we've discussed before,

34

00:01:56,930  -->  00:01:59,885
we can use the softmax function for this.

35

00:01:59,885  -->  00:02:03,220
The output here will have the same shape as before,

36

00:02:03,220  -->  00:02:08,580
but now these values will be probabilities our model have assigned for each token,

37

00:02:08,580  -->  00:02:13,440
and the sum of probabilities for each position is equal to one.
